'''Umashimaji no Mikoto''' (宇摩志麻遅命) is regarded as the progenitor of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏}}, {{ill|Hozumi clan|ja|穂積氏}}, and {{ill|Uneme clan|ja|采女氏}}. The name "Umashimaji no Mikoto" is used in the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}''.
== Overview ==
In the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}'', the name appears as '''Umashimaji no Mikoto''', while the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'' uses '''Kamimade no Mikoto''' (可美真手命), and the ''{{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀}}'' lists it as '''Ajimami no Mikoto''' (味間見命).
Born to {{ill|Nigihayahi no Mikoto|ja|邇芸速日命}} and {{ill|Tomiya-hime|ja|登美夜毘売}}, Umashimaji no Mikoto initially served {{ill|Nagasu Negihiko|ja|長髄彦}} but later defected to {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}, aiding in his {{ill|Jimmu's Eastern Expedition|lt=Eastern Campaign|ja|神武東征}}. According to the ''Sendai Kuji Hongi'', Umashimaji killed Nagasu Negihiko and pledged allegiance to Emperor Jimmu, subsequently leading the Mononobe clan in safeguarding the imperial court.<ref>In the ''Nihon Shoki'', these actions are attributed to Nigihayahi no Mikoto (''Emperor Jimmu, Preface to Accession, 12th Month'').</ref>
The ''Sendai Kuji Hongi'' also recounts that after Emperor Jimmu's accession, Umashimaji offered the ten ''amatsushirushi no mitakara'' (天璽瑞宝, heavenly treasures) left behind by Nigihayahi, using them in rituals to calm the spirits of the emperor and empress. This practice became the origin of the modern {{ill|Chinkonsai|ja|鎮魂祭}}.
According to the tradition of {{ill|Mononobe Shrine|ja|物部神社 (大田市)}}, Umashimaji died in {{ill|Iwami Province|ja|石見国}} after pacifying the Mino and Koshi regions. His grave is believed to be located behind the shrine's main hall. Similar traditions are also found at {{ill|Yahiko Shrine|ja|彌彦神社}} and {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮}}.
