According to the tradition of {{ill|Mononobe Shrine|ja|物部神社 (大田市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mononobe Shrine|qq=}}, Umashimaji died in {{ill|Iwami Province|ja|石見国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwami Province|qq=}} after pacifying the Mino and Koshi regions. His grave is believed to be located behind the shrine's main hall. Similar traditions are also found at {{ill|Yahiko Shrine|ja|彌彦神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yahiko Shrine|qq=}} and {{ill|Isonokami Jingu|lt=Isonokami Jingu|lt=Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Isonokami Shrine|qq=}}.

The prefix "Umashi" denotes beauty or excellence, while the root "Machi," "Mate," or "Mami" likely refers to divinatory skill, suggesting a connection to divination practices.<ref name=kuroda>{{Cite journal|author=Tatsuya Kuroda|title=Restorative Studies on the Genealogy of the Mononobe Clan in the ''Tenson Honki'' (Part I)|journal=Research Bulletin of Osaka Prefecture University Technical College|volume=48|pages=1–14|doi=10.24729/00007548|year=2014|url=https://doi.org/10.24729/00007548}}</ref>

