{{infobox deity | name = Umashimaji no Mikoto (宇摩志麻遅命) | image = Umashimaji.png | image_size = | caption = Umashimaji (from [[:en:Kikuchi Yōsai|Yōsai Kikuchi]]'s ''[[:en:Zenken Kojitsu|Zenken Kojitsu]]'') | period = [[Ancient Japan]] | birth_date = Unknown | death_date = Unknown | other_names = Kamimade no Mikoto, Ajimami no Mikoto, Ajima Chichino Mikoto | titles = [[Sukune|Ashini]], Chief of Provincial Governance (申食国大夫) | allegiance = [[Emperor Jimmu]] | clan = {{ill|Hozumi clan|ja|穂積氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hozumi clan|qq=}}, [[:en:Mononobe clan|Mononobe clan]] | parents = Father: {{ill|Nigihayahi|lt=Nigihayahi no Mikoto|ja|邇芸速日命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nigihayahi|qq=}}; Mother: {{ill|Tomiya-hime|ja|登美夜毘売|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomiya-hime|qq=}} | siblings = {{ill|Niyaho no Hime|ja|熟穂屋姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Niyaho no Hime|qq=}}, {{ill|Ikakoya-hime|ja|伊加古夜日売命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikakoya-hime|qq=}}, Possibly {{ill|Amakaga-yama no Mikoto|ja|天香山命|1=Ame-no-Kaguyama|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amakaga-yama no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Kaguyama|qq=}} | spouse = {{ill|Shinaga-hime|ja|師長姫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinaga-hime|qq=}} | children = {{ill|Hikoyuki no Mikoto|ja|彦湯支命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hikoyuki no Mikoto|qq=}}, {{ill|Ajitsukitada no Mikoto|ja|味饒田命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ajitsukitada no Mikoto|qq=}} }}
'''Umashimaji no Mikoto''' (宇摩志麻遅命) is regarded as the progenitor of the [[:en:Mononobe clan|Mononobe clan]], {{ill|Hozumi clan|ja|穂積氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hozumi clan|qq=}}, and {{ill|Saiyō Clan|ja|采女氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uneme clan|qq=}}. The name "Umashimaji no Mikoto" is used in the ''[[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]''.
== Overview ==
In the ''[[:en:Kojiki|Kojiki]]'', the name appears as '''Umashimaji no Mikoto''', while the ''[[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]]'' uses '''Kamimade no Mikoto''' (可美真手命), and the ''[[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]]'' lists it as '''Ajimami no Mikoto''' (味間見命).
Born to {{ill|Nigihayahi|lt=Nigihayahi no Mikoto|ja|邇芸速日命|fr|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nigihayahi|qq=}} and {{ill|Tomiya-hime|ja|登美夜毘売|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomiya-hime|qq=}}, Umashimaji no Mikoto initially served {{ill|Nagatsuhiko|lt=Nagatsuhiko|lt=Nagasu Negihiko|ja|長髄彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagasu Negihiko|qq=}} but later defected to [[:en:Emperor Jimmu|Emperor Jimmu]], aiding in his [[:en:Jimmu's Eastern Expedition|Eastern Campaign]]. According to the ''Sendai Kuji Hongi'', Umashimaji killed Nagasu Negihiko and pledged allegiance to Emperor Jimmu, subsequently leading the Mononobe clan in safeguarding the imperial court.<ref>In the ''Nihon Shoki'', these actions are attributed to Nigihayahi no Mikoto (''Emperor Jimmu, Preface to Accession, 12th Month'').</ref>
The ''Sendai Kuji Hongi'' also recounts that after Emperor Jimmu's accession, Umashimaji offered the ten ''amatsushirushi no mitakara'' (天璽瑞宝, heavenly treasures) left behind by Nigihayahi, using them in rituals to calm the spirits of the emperor and empress. This practice became the origin of the modern {{ill|Chinkon-sai|ja|鎮魂祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinkon-sai|qq=}}.
According to the tradition of [[:en:Mononobe Shrine|Mononobe Shrine]], Umashimaji died in [[:en:Iwami Province|Iwami Province]] after pacifying the Mino and Koshi regions. His grave is believed to be located behind the shrine's main hall. Similar traditions are also found at [[:en:Yahiko Shrine|Yahiko Shrine]] and [[:en:Isonokami Shrine|Isonokami Shrine]].
The prefix "Umashi" denotes beauty or excellence, while the root "Machi," "Mate," or "Mami" likely refers to divinatory skill, suggesting a connection to divination practices.<ref name=kuroda>{{Cite journal|author=Tatsuya Kuroda|title=Restorative Studies on the Genealogy of the Mononobe Clan in the ''Tenson Honki'' (Part I)|journal=Research Bulletin of Osaka Prefecture University Technical College|volume=48|pages=1–14|doi=10.24729/00007548|year=2014|url=https://doi.org/10.24729/00007548}}</ref>
== Principal Shrines == * [[:en:Mononobe Shrine|Mononobe Shrine]] ([[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]], [[:en:Ōda, Shimane|Ōda]]): The supposed burial site of Umashimaji no Mikoto. * {{ill|Ajima Shrine|ja|味鋺神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ajima Shrine|qq=}} ([[:en:Aichi Prefecture|Aichi Prefecture]], [[:en:Nagoya|Nagoya]]): Located near the Ajima Kofun Group. * [[:en:Isonokami Shrine|Isonokami Shrine]] ([[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]], [[:en:Tenri, Nara|Tenri]]): Founded after the transfer of the Futsumitama Sword, which Umashimaji enshrined. * {{ill|Ishikiri Tsurugiya Shrine|ja|石切剣箭神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikiri Tsurugiya Shrine|qq=}} ([[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]], [[:en:Higashiōsaka|Higashiōsaka]]): Established by Umashimaji in honor of Nigihayahi.
